text.tspan: This is a chart of the ionising radiation dose a person can
absorb from various sources. The unit for absorbed dose
is "sievert" (Sv), and measures the effect that a dose of
radiation will have on the cells of the body. One sievert (all at
once) will make you sick, and too many more will kill you, but
we safely absorb small amounts of natural radiation daily.
Note: The small number of sieverts absorbed in a shorter time
will generally cause more damage, but cumulative long-term
dose plays a big role in things like cancer risk.
Living within 50 miles of a nuclear
power plant for a year (0.09 μSv)
Living within 50 miles of a coal
power plant for a year (0.3 μSv)
Using a CRT monitor for a year (1 μSv)

Airplane flight from New York to LA (40 μSv)
Using a cell phone (0 μSv) - a cell phone's transmitter does
not produce ionizing radiation* and does not cause cancer.
